  "prompt": "I got hit in the head. I feel pins and needles in my hands and feet and the right side of my face is numb. Should I go to the hospital or wait?",
  "response": "**You should go to the hospital immediately.** These symptoms, especially after a head injury, are concerning and could indicate a serious medical condition.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Head Injury:** Any head injury can cause a concussion or more severe brain trauma.\n*   **Numbness and Tingling:** Numbness and tingling (paresthesia), especially on one side of the face and in the hands and feet, can be a sign of nerve damage or pressure on the brain or spinal cord.\n*   **Possible Conditions:** These symptoms could potentially be related to a concussion, stroke, transient ischemic attack (TIA), hematoma, or other neurological issues.\n\n**Do not wait to see if the symptoms improve.** Prompt medical evaluation is crucial to diagnose the cause and receive appropriate treatment.\n\n**While waiting for help or en route to the hospital:**\n\n*   **Avoid moving unnecessarily:** Stabilize your head and neck if possible.\n*   **Inform emergency responders:** Let them know you had a head injury and the symptoms you're experiencing.\n*   **Do not take any medication (pain relievers, etc.)** unless directed by medical personnel.\n*   **Have someone stay with you** to monitor your condition.\n*   **If you feel like you are going to throw up, turn on your side** to prevent choking.\n\nTime is of the essence in these situations. Please seek immediate medical attention.\n",
